</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Acute mesenteric ischemia is a rare life-threatening condition that accounts for approximately one in 1000 hospital admissions. The mortality rate is 50%–69% owing to the absence of specific symptoms and laboratory data, which makes early detection of this condition difficult. If the use of contrast material is possible, biphasic contrast material–enhanced multidetector computed tomography (CT) is the first-line imaging test for early diagnosis of the disease and for differentiation from other causes of acute abdomen. Multidetector CT can depict mesenteric ischemia, its underlying causes, and its severity. Mesenteric ischemia is classified as either acute or chronic. The causes of AMI include arterial embolism, arterial thrombosis, venous thrombosis, and nonocclusive mesenteric ischemia, among which arterial causes are far more common than venous causes. Recently, endovascular procedures such as thrombolysis, thrombectomy, thrombus fragmentation, and stent placement have been successfully and safely performed when the ischemia is reversible.</div><div role="paragraph"><i><a href="https://images.rsna.org/index.html?doi=10.1148/rg.2018170163"><i>Online DICOM image stacks are available for this article.</i></a></i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2018</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170163">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170163">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig1a.jpeg" height="1544" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Portomesenteric venous thrombosis in a 51-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows prominent bowel wall thickening (arrows). <a href="https://images.rsna.org/index.html?doi=10.1148/rg.2018170163&amp;fig=fig1a">(A full DICOM image stack is available online.)</a> <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a thickened bowel wall and a target or halo appearance (arrowheads). Mesenteric stranding and vascular engorgement (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) are also seen. <b>(c)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows thrombi (arrows) in the SMV and portal vein. <a href="https://images.rsna.org/index.html?doi=10.1148/rg.2018170163&amp;fig=fig1a">(A full DICOM image stack is available online.)</a><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig1b.jpeg" height="1503" width="1726" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Portomesenteric venous thrombosis in a 51-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows prominent bowel wall thickening (arrows). <a href="https://images.rsna.org/index.html?doi=10.1148/rg.2018170163&amp;fig=fig1b">(A full DICOM image stack is available online.)</a> <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a thickened bowel wall and a target or halo appearance (arrowheads). Mesenteric stranding and vascular engorgement (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) are also seen. <b>(c)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows thrombi (arrows) in the SMV and portal vein. <a href="https://images.rsna.org/index.html?doi=10.1148/rg.2018170163&amp;fig=fig1b">(A full DICOM image stack is available online.)</a><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig1c.jpeg" height="1508" width="1390" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Portomesenteric venous thrombosis in a 51-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows prominent bowel wall thickening (arrows). <a href="https://images.rsna.org/index.html?doi=10.1148/rg.2018170163&amp;fig=fig1c">(A full DICOM image stack is available online.)</a> <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a thickened bowel wall and a target or halo appearance (arrowheads). Mesenteric stranding and vascular engorgement (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) are also seen. <b>(c)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows thrombi (arrows) in the SMV and portal vein. <a href="https://images.rsna.org/index.html?doi=10.1148/rg.2018170163&amp;fig=fig1c">(A full DICOM image stack is available online.)</a><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig2a.jpeg" height="1319" width="1743" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. SMA embolism and arterial reperfusion in a 63-year-old man who experienced severe abdominal pain while undergoing treatment of atrial fibrillation. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the upper abdomen shows a filling defect corresponding to an embolus (arrow) in the SMA. Segmental infarction of the left kidney (arrowheads) is also seen. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT of the lower abdomen shows a thickened small bowel, with the wall showing a halo or target pattern (arrowheads) of contrast enhancement, which is compatible with the appearance of ischemic bowel after arterial reperfusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig2b.jpeg" height="1319" width="1807" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. SMA embolism and arterial reperfusion in a 63-year-old man who experienced severe abdominal pain while undergoing treatment of atrial fibrillation. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the upper abdomen shows a filling defect corresponding to an embolus (arrow) in the SMA. Segmental infarction of the left kidney (arrowheads) is also seen. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT of the lower abdomen shows a thickened small bowel, with the wall showing a halo or target pattern (arrowheads) of contrast enhancement, which is compatible with the appearance of ischemic bowel after arterial reperfusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig3a.jpeg" height="1300" width="1765" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. SMA embolism in a 71-year-old woman with a history of atrial fibrillation who experienced severe abdominal pain. Craniocaudal contrast-enhanced CT images of the abdomen show segmental infarction (arrow in <b>a</b>) of the spleen, an embolus (arrow in <b>b</b>) in the SMA, and lack of contrast enhancement in the small bowel loops (arrows in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig3b.jpeg" height="1286" width="1785" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. SMA embolism in a 71-year-old woman with a history of atrial fibrillation who experienced severe abdominal pain. Craniocaudal contrast-enhanced CT images of the abdomen show segmental infarction (arrow in <b>a</b>) of the spleen, an embolus (arrow in <b>b</b>) in the SMA, and lack of contrast enhancement in the small bowel loops (arrows in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig3c.jpeg" height="1323" width="1913" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. SMA embolism in a 71-year-old woman with a history of atrial fibrillation who experienced severe abdominal pain. Craniocaudal contrast-enhanced CT images of the abdomen show segmental infarction (arrow in <b>a</b>) of the spleen, an embolus (arrow in <b>b</b>) in the SMA, and lack of contrast enhancement in the small bowel loops (arrows in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig4a.jpeg" height="1122" width="1794" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Transmural small bowel infarction due to SMA thrombosis in a 73-year-old woman with a history of atrial fibrillation. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image of the abdomen shows a slightly high-attenuating bowel wall (arrows) over long segments. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and venous phase <b>(c)</b> CT images of the abdomen show that the wall of the involved bowel segments (arrows) lacks contrast enhancement. However, the uninvolved segments of the small bowel (arrowheads) show contrast enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig4b.jpeg" height="1208" width="1765" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Transmural small bowel infarction due to SMA thrombosis in a 73-year-old woman with a history of atrial fibrillation. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image of the abdomen shows a slightly high-attenuating bowel wall (arrows) over long segments. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and venous phase <b>(c)</b> CT images of the abdomen show that the wall of the involved bowel segments (arrows) lacks contrast enhancement. However, the uninvolved segments of the small bowel (arrowheads) show contrast enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig4c.jpeg" height="1208" width="1988" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Transmural small bowel infarction due to SMA thrombosis in a 73-year-old woman with a history of atrial fibrillation. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image of the abdomen shows a slightly high-attenuating bowel wall (arrows) over long segments. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and venous phase <b>(c)</b> CT images of the abdomen show that the wall of the involved bowel segments (arrows) lacks contrast enhancement. However, the uninvolved segments of the small bowel (arrowheads) show contrast enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig5.jpeg" height="1340" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. SMA embolism in a 76-year-old woman. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows dilated bowel loops associated with air-fluid levels (arrowheads), indicating a state of ileus. The bowel wall (arrows) is thin (paper-thin wall) and lacks contrast enhancement. Mesenteric stranding and ascites (<b>*</b>) are also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig6a.jpeg" height="1328" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. NOMI with transmural bowel infarction in a 78-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show gas (arrows) in the bowel wall (pneumatosis intestinalis) at the distal ileum and ascending colon. Gas is seen in the branches of the mesenteric vein (arrowheads in <b>b</b>), and mesenteric stranding (<b>*</b> in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) in those areas is also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig6b.jpeg" height="1383" width="1843" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. NOMI with transmural bowel infarction in a 78-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show gas (arrows) in the bowel wall (pneumatosis intestinalis) at the distal ileum and ascending colon. Gas is seen in the branches of the mesenteric vein (arrowheads in <b>b</b>), and mesenteric stranding (<b>*</b> in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) in those areas is also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig6c.jpeg" height="1402" width="1306" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. NOMI with transmural bowel infarction in a 78-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show gas (arrows) in the bowel wall (pneumatosis intestinalis) at the distal ileum and ascending colon. Gas is seen in the branches of the mesenteric vein (arrowheads in <b>b</b>), and mesenteric stranding (<b>*</b> in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) in those areas is also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig7.jpeg" height="1206" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. SMA embolism. Axial nonenhanced CT image shows the high-attenuating major trunk of the SMA (arrow), a finding indicative of an embolus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig8a.jpeg" height="1095" width="1827" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Reversible bowel ischemia caused by an SMA embolism in a 65-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an SMA embolus (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and venous phase <b>(c)</b> CT images show bowel loops (arrows) with inferior diminished contrast enhancement compared with that of the uninvolved bowel loops, which demonstrate apparent contrast enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig8b.jpeg" height="1094" width="1924" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Reversible bowel ischemia caused by an SMA embolism in a 65-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an SMA embolus (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and venous phase <b>(c)</b> CT images show bowel loops (arrows) with inferior diminished contrast enhancement compared with that of the uninvolved bowel loops, which demonstrate apparent contrast enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig8c.jpeg" height="1024" width="1804" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Reversible bowel ischemia caused by an SMA embolism in a 65-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an SMA embolus (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and venous phase <b>(c)</b> CT images show bowel loops (arrows) with inferior diminished contrast enhancement compared with that of the uninvolved bowel loops, which demonstrate apparent contrast enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig9a.jpeg" height="1435" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Irreversible bowel ischemia from an SMA embolism in an 85-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows an occluding embolus (arrows) in the SMA and its branches. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and venous phase <b>(c)</b> CT images show that the bowel wall (arrowheads) lacks contrast enhancement. The bowel loops are dilated, reflecting paralytic ileus due to loss of muscular tone. The bowel wall is thin (paper-thin wall).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig9b.jpeg" height="1239" width="1878" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Irreversible bowel ischemia from an SMA embolism in an 85-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows an occluding embolus (arrows) in the SMA and its branches. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and venous phase <b>(c)</b> CT images show that the bowel wall (arrowheads) lacks contrast enhancement. The bowel loops are dilated, reflecting paralytic ileus due to loss of muscular tone. The bowel wall is thin (paper-thin wall).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig9c.jpeg" height="1239" width="1826" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Irreversible bowel ischemia from an SMA embolism in an 85-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows an occluding embolus (arrows) in the SMA and its branches. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and venous phase <b>(c)</b> CT images show that the bowel wall (arrowheads) lacks contrast enhancement. The bowel loops are dilated, reflecting paralytic ileus due to loss of muscular tone. The bowel wall is thin (paper-thin wall).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig10.jpeg" height="1279" width="1771" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. SMA embolism. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows the SMA trunk (white arrow), which lacks contrast enhancement owing to an embolus. The thrombosed SMA is dilated and is as large as the adjacent SMV (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig11a.jpeg" height="1807" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. SMA thrombosis in a 64-year-old man with chronic renal failure who required treatment with dialysis. Sagittal CT <b>(a)</b> and oblique sagittal MIP <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced images shows prominent calcification of the aortic wall and the wall of the origin of the celiac trunk (arrowheads) and the SMA (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig11b.jpeg" height="1807" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. SMA thrombosis in a 64-year-old man with chronic renal failure who required treatment with dialysis. Sagittal CT <b>(a)</b> and oblique sagittal MIP <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced images shows prominent calcification of the aortic wall and the wall of the origin of the celiac trunk (arrowheads) and the SMA (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig12a.jpeg" height="1457" width="1866" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. SMA thrombosis in a 52-year-old man with chronic renal failure requiring treatment with dialysis. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows prominent calcification (arrow) of the aortic wall and the wall of the origin of the SMA. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and venous phase <b>(c)</b> CT images show no bowel wall enhancement (arrowheads). The bowel loops are dilated, reflecting paralytic ileus owing to loss of muscular tone.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig12b.jpeg" height="1487" width="1883" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. SMA thrombosis in a 52-year-old man with chronic renal failure requiring treatment with dialysis. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows prominent calcification (arrow) of the aortic wall and the wall of the origin of the SMA. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and venous phase <b>(c)</b> CT images show no bowel wall enhancement (arrowheads). The bowel loops are dilated, reflecting paralytic ileus owing to loss of muscular tone.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig12c.jpeg" height="1437" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. SMA thrombosis in a 52-year-old man with chronic renal failure requiring treatment with dialysis. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows prominent calcification (arrow) of the aortic wall and the wall of the origin of the SMA. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and venous phase <b>(c)</b> CT images show no bowel wall enhancement (arrowheads). The bowel loops are dilated, reflecting paralytic ileus owing to loss of muscular tone.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig13a.jpeg" height="1528" width="1397" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. NOMI in an 86-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows dilatation of the involved bowel segments. The degree of enhancement of the bowel wall is diminished. The SMA and its branches look thin, but no obstruction of the vessels (arrowheads) is seen. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates dilatation of the involved bowel segments. The degree of wall enhancement (arrows) is decreased when compared with uninvolved segments.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig13b.jpeg" height="1528" width="1959" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. NOMI in an 86-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows dilatation of the involved bowel segments. The degree of enhancement of the bowel wall is diminished. The SMA and its branches look thin, but no obstruction of the vessels (arrowheads) is seen. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates dilatation of the involved bowel segments. The degree of wall enhancement (arrows) is decreased when compared with uninvolved segments.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig14a.jpeg" height="1155" width="1886" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. NOMI with arterial reperfusion in a 90-year-old woman with abdominal pain. The patient was treated conservatively, and prominent bowel thickening manifested after arterial reperfusion. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows the thickened bowel (arrows) with homogeneous attenuation. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and venous phase <b>(c)</b> CT images show a halo or target pattern (arrowheads) of contrast enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig14b.jpeg" height="1146" width="1862" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. NOMI with arterial reperfusion in a 90-year-old woman with abdominal pain. The patient was treated conservatively, and prominent bowel thickening manifested after arterial reperfusion. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows the thickened bowel (arrows) with homogeneous attenuation. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and venous phase <b>(c)</b> CT images show a halo or target pattern (arrowheads) of contrast enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig14c.jpeg" height="1150" width="1804" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. NOMI with arterial reperfusion in a 90-year-old woman with abdominal pain. The patient was treated conservatively, and prominent bowel thickening manifested after arterial reperfusion. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows the thickened bowel (arrows) with homogeneous attenuation. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and venous phase <b>(c)</b> CT images show a halo or target pattern (arrowheads) of contrast enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig15a.jpeg" height="1573" width="1574" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. SMA embolism (same patient as in <a href="#fig8a">Fig 8</a>). <b>(a)</b> Posteroanterior digital subtraction angiographic (DSA) image shows the SMA disrupted by an embolus (arrow) near the orifice of the middle colic artery, although collateral circulation to the bowel is visible. <b>(b)</b> Posteroanterior DSA image shows revascularization of the main SMA (arrowheads) after endovascular treatment with thrombectomy and thrombolysis was performed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig15b.jpeg" height="1573" width="1581" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. SMA embolism (same patient as in <a href="#fig8a">Fig 8</a>). <b>(a)</b> Posteroanterior digital subtraction angiographic (DSA) image shows the SMA disrupted by an embolus (arrow) near the orifice of the middle colic artery, although collateral circulation to the bowel is visible. <b>(b)</b> Posteroanterior DSA image shows revascularization of the main SMA (arrowheads) after endovascular treatment with thrombectomy and thrombolysis was performed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig16a.jpeg" height="1512" width="1838" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. SMA thrombosis in an 85-year-old man with abdominal pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show stenosis (arrows) at the origin of the SMA. <b>(c)</b> DSA image shows a metallic stent (arrows) in the stenotic region of the SMA, which was placed after balloon angioplasty.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig16b.jpeg" height="1487" width="1493" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. SMA thrombosis in an 85-year-old man with abdominal pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show stenosis (arrows) at the origin of the SMA. <b>(c)</b> DSA image shows a metallic stent (arrows) in the stenotic region of the SMA, which was placed after balloon angioplasty.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig16c.jpeg" height="1291" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span>. SMA thrombosis in an 85-year-old man with abdominal pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show stenosis (arrows) at the origin of the SMA. <b>(c)</b> DSA image shows a metallic stent (arrows) in the stenotic region of the SMA, which was placed after balloon angioplasty.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig17a.jpeg" height="1575" width="1579" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Venous thrombosis in a 63-year-old man with abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Arterial phase DSA image obtained before EVT does not show occlusion of the SMA or its branches. <b>(b)</b> Venous phase DSA image shows the branches of the SMV (arrowheads) but does not show the main trunk of the SMV or the portal vein. Urokinase was continuously injected through a catheter placed in the SMA. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained 3 weeks later shows the remaining venous thrombi (white arrow) and collateral circulation (black arrow) compensating for hepatoportal blood flow. Although the patient’s symptoms were relieved after treatment, complete thrombolysis was not achieved.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig17b.jpeg" height="1574" width="1577" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Venous thrombosis in a 63-year-old man with abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Arterial phase DSA image obtained before EVT does not show occlusion of the SMA or its branches. <b>(b)</b> Venous phase DSA image shows the branches of the SMV (arrowheads) but does not show the main trunk of the SMV or the portal vein. Urokinase was continuously injected through a catheter placed in the SMA. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained 3 weeks later shows the remaining venous thrombi (white arrow) and collateral circulation (black arrow) compensating for hepatoportal blood flow. Although the patient’s symptoms were relieved after treatment, complete thrombolysis was not achieved.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig17c.jpeg" height="1224" width="1756" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span>. Venous thrombosis in a 63-year-old man with abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Arterial phase DSA image obtained before EVT does not show occlusion of the SMA or its branches. <b>(b)</b> Venous phase DSA image shows the branches of the SMV (arrowheads) but does not show the main trunk of the SMV or the portal vein. Urokinase was continuously injected through a catheter placed in the SMA. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained 3 weeks later shows the remaining venous thrombi (white arrow) and collateral circulation (black arrow) compensating for hepatoportal blood flow. Although the patient’s symptoms were relieved after treatment, complete thrombolysis was not achieved.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig18a.jpeg" height="1403" width="1541" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. NOMI in an 86-year-old woman (same patient as seen in <a href="#fig13a">Fig 13</a>). <b>(a)</b> DSA image demonstrates vasospasm (arrowheads) of the SMA and its branches. Enhancement of the bowel wall is diminished. <b>(b)</b> DSA image obtained after continuous intra-arterial infusion with papaverine hydrochloride shows the relieved spasm of the arterial branches (arrowheads) and improvement of bowel wall enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170163/asset/images/large/rg.2018170163.fig18b.jpeg" height="1403" width="1609" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. NOMI in an 86-year-old woman (same patient as seen in <a href="#fig13a">Fig 13</a>). <b>(a)</b> DSA image demonstrates vasospasm (arrowheads) of the SMA and its branches. Enhancement of the bowel wall is diminished. <b>(b)</b> DSA image obtained after continuous intra-arterial infusion with papaverine hydrochloride shows the relieved spasm of the arterial branches (arrowheads) and improvement of bowel wall enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170163&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Stoney RJ, Cunningham CG. Acute mesenteric ischemia. <em>Surgery</em> 1993;114(3):489–490.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8367801/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Acute+mesenteric+ischemia&amp;author=RJ+Stoney&amp;author=CG+Cunningham&amp;publication_year=1993&amp;journal=Surgery&amp;pages=489-490&amp;pmid=8367801">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div clas